Title: The only computer science book worth reading twice?
Description:
I was talking to one of my students earlier, and lent him a book to
read over summer. It was only after he’d left that I realised that —
for me at any rate — the book I’d given him is probably the most
seminal work in the whole of computer science, and certainly the book
that’s most influenced my career and research interests.

Title: Reverse Engineering a trojan Telegram Clone
Description:
Telegram is one of the largest platforms where individuals can commit digital crimes without being noticed, unless someone reports their content.
You can easily find related material with a simple search through channels. On channels managed by Iranians, in particular, there are sometimes disturbing contents like child abuse, violence, and more.
Additionally, it can be an ideal platform for deploying trojan on a large scale.

Title: ByeBye "Expert": Refactoring Prompts
Description:
When using AI to generate code, I keep running into the same frustrating problem: it tends to split my code excessively. A single function gets broken into multiple smaller ones, and a single file becomes a collection of scattered files. It seems to believe this approach aligns with “industry best practices.”
Take a simple task like sendMessage(user, message). Instead of keeping it straightforward, the AI splits it into a message builder, a message sender, message types, and so on—scattered across five or six files.

Title: Next-Gen PDF Interactions with IronPDF, C#, and Blazor!
Description:
Dive into the future of PDF management! In this video, we explore how to leverage IronPDF, C#, and Blazor to enable powerful AI-driven interactions with your PDF documents.  We'll use .NET Aspire and a new IronPDF container to enable amazing PDF management capabilities. Discover how ChromaDb and semantic kernel bring advanced AI capabilities to analyze, summarize, and chat about the contents of any PDF.

What You'll Learn:
- Setting up IronPDF, C#, and Blazor for seamless integration.
- Utilizing ChromaDb and semantic kernel for intelligent content analysis.
- Implementing AI-driven chat functionalities to interact with PDF contents.
- Practical demonstrations and real-world applications.

Join us for this exciting journey into the next generation of PDF interactions and transform how you work with PDF documents!

Get your copy of the source code for this demo at:  https://github.com/iron-software/IronPdf.Aspire.AI

#ironpdf #csharp #blazor #dotnet

Title: Stop Making Me Memorize The Borrow Checker
Description: I started learning Rust about 3 or 4 years ago. I am now knee-deep in several very complex Rust projects that keep slamming into the limitations of the Rust compiler. One of the most common and obnoxious problems is hitting a situation the borrow-checker can’t deal with and realizing that I need to completely re-architect how my program works, because lifetimes are “contagious” the same way async is. Naturally, Rust has both!
